DESCRIPTION:This assignment is to get you started on [Assignment 8: Jerry-T
 ac-Toe] (https://butler.instructure.com/courses/54110/assignments/530974).
   \n\n1.  Create a new folder for this assignment.  \n\n2.  Create a
  class called JerryTacToe.  Create a constructor which displays "Welcome 
 to Jerry-Tac-Toe!"\n\n3.  Write main in a different file from your class.
   Make a new JerryTacToe object.  Compile and run your program and make 
 sure your welcome message from Step 2 is displayed.\n\n4.  Now in main\, 
 make an array of 10 characters called board as discussed in class.  Initi
 alize your array.  Cell 0 should contain an 'X' indicating it will be ign
 ored.  The rest of the cells should contain a '-' indicating no one has p
 layed yet.  Compile your program.\n\n5.  Write a method in your class ca
 lled printBoard() which displays your array.  It should take your board a
 s a parameter.  It should only print cells 1-9\, and it should print cell
 s 1\, 2\, 3 on the first line\, 4\, 5\, 6 on the second line\, and 7\, 8\,
  9 on the third line\, like the actual Jerry Tac Toe board.   (Remember 
 we are ignoring cell 0.)  Call your method from main and compile and run 
 your program.\n\n6.  Write a method called playerTurn() which takes two p
 arameters:  your board and an integer indicating the spot the user wants 
 to play.  Your method should put an 'P' in that spot in the array indicat
 ing the player has moved there and return the array.   Call this method 
 from main assuming the player chooses to play in spot 1.  Then print your
  board to confirm it has been updated.\n\n7.  Write a method called compu
 terTurn() which takes your board as a parameter.  For now\, the computer 
 will play in spot 2.  Update your array to put an 'C' in that spot in the
  array indicating the computer has moved there.  Call this method from ma
 in\, and then print your board to confirm it has been updated.\n\n8.  Mod
 ify main so that it asks the user to choose where to play (so now they can
  choose any spot\, not just spot 1).  Also modify playerTurn() so that if
  the player tries to play in a spot that has already been taken an error m
 essage is printed (and the board is unchanged).  Test this.\n\n9.  Modif
 y computerTurn() so that it finds the first unused spot to play (so that i
 t is not always playing in spot 2).  Test this by printing your board to 
 be sure it works.\n\n10.  Now in main\, create a loop that goes around 4 
 times\, so that the user plays\, then the computer plays\, then the user p
 lays again\, and then the computer plays again.  Print the board after ea
 ch turn to be sure it is correct.\n\n11.  In your class\, add a method ca
 lled checkDraw() which returns a boolean.  It should return true if there
  are no empty spaces left on the board\, and false otherwise.  (Right now
  we are not worrying about detecting whether someone has won -we are assum
 ing that if the board is full\, no one won\, which obviously might not be 
 true.)  Modify your loop in main to play until there are no more empty sp
 aces.  To do this\, someone should play\, then check to see if there is a
  draw\, and if not someone else gets to play\, then check to see if there 
 is a draw\, etc.\n\n12.  Now\, work on checkWin() which should return tru
 e if someone has won and false otherwise.  Modify main so that after some
 one plays\, you now check to see if checkWin() is true.  If it is\, the g
 ame is over.  If it is not\, check for a draw.  If there is a draw\, the
  game is over.  Otherwise\, play continues.\n\nPlay your game a lot and b
 e proud!
