DESCRIPTION:***********\nDescription\n***********\n\nThere is an easy and w
 ell-known formula for computing π based on the sum of the reciprocals of 
 the squares. It is:\n\n       1+1/4+1/9+1/16+1/25+... = π2/6.\n\nThis
  sum is infinite\, but we can get a good approximation by adding up\, say\
 , the first 10\,000 terms. If we do that\, we get\n\n \n\n        sum
  = 1+1/4+1/9+1/16+1/25+...+1/(10000)2\n\nand the estimate π=sqrt(6*sum).\
 n\n \n\nWrite a parallel program\, using either chunking or striping (you
 r choice) to compute an estimate for π this way. Allow the user to specif
 y how far to take the sum.\n\n \n\nSubmit code on-line\n\n \n\n*********
 ***************\nExtra Credit (10 points)\n************************\n\nThe
 re are other formulas\, based on numeric integration or summations\, to co
 mpute π that are more efficient than the one given here.\n\nFor 10 points
  extra credit\, implement a formula based on using the trapezoid rule or s
 impson's rule with numeric integration\, or one of the more complex summat
 ion formulas. (If you are not sure if a particular formula qualifies\, jus
 t ask me.) Be sure to indicate the formula you are using and where you fou
 nd it in your comments.\n\n \n\n*****\nNotes\n*****\n\n* If you compute t
 he sum from the low end first\, ending at 1\, your estimates will be much 
 better.\n\n* Don't forget to write comments\, and be sure to put your name
 (s) in the comments at the top of your program. Remember to indent properl
 y.\n\n* Start early!\n\n* Do this program in stages. First\, get a program
  to simply print "hello" from each processor. Then\, set up for chunking o
 r striping and make sure each processor knows what it is supposed to do. P
 rint out intermediate results to make sure everything is working as you ex
 pect it to.\n\n* You may use MPI_Send and MPI_Recv\, or you can use mor
 e advanced functions\, like broadcast and reduce\, as you see fit.\n\n* Ge
 t the basic program working before trying any of the extra credit\, and wh
 en you do start working on the extra credit\, save a copy of your basic pr
 ogram in a separate file\, just in case.\n\n \n\n \n\n \n\n \n\n 
